T1  - Economic Stimulus at the Expense of Routine-Task Jobs
AU  - TUZEL, SELALE
AU  - ZHANG, MIAO BEN
Y1  - 2021/12/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13080
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 3347
EP  - 3399
VL  - 76
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13080
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Do investment tax incentives improve job prospects for workers? We explore states' adoption of a major federal tax incentive that accelerates the depreciation of equipment investments for eligible firms but not for ineligible ones. Analyzing massive establishment-level data sets on occupational employment and computer investment, we find that when states expand investment incentives, eligible firms immediately increase their equipment and skilled employees; whereas they reduce routine-task employees after a delay of up to two years. These opposing effects constitute an overall insignificant effect on the firms' total employment and shed light on the nuances of job creation through investment incentives.
ER  - 

